    <section class="services" id="services1">
    <h3 class="heading">About</h3>
    <div class="box-contentainer">
        <div class="box">
            <h3>Education</h3>
            <p><b> Rates: </b>In some regions, gender disparities in education can be reflected in varying enrollment rates between boys and girls. Socioeconomic factors, cultural norms, and accessibility contribute to these differences.
                Dropout Rates: Boys may experience higher dropout rates, influenced by factors such as academic performance, socio-economic conditions, and societal expectations regarding gender roles.
                Access to Higher Education: While strides have been made globally, access to higher education may still be influenced by gender biases, limiting certain fields of study for men or women.</p>
            <a href="#" class="btn">learn more<span class="fas fa-chevron-right"></span></a>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <h3>Health</h3>
            <p><b>Heart Disease:</b> Men tend to face higher rates of heart disease, often associated with lifestyle factors, including diet, exercise, and stress.
                Suicide Rates: Men are more likely to die by suicide, which can be influenced by societal expectations around emotional expression, mental health stigma, and reluctance to seek help.
                Workplace-Related Injuries: Occupations traditionally dominated by men, such as construction or manufacturing, may expose them to higher rates of workplace injuries.</p>
            <a href="#" class="btn">learn more<span class="fas fa-chevron-right"></span></a>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <h3>Workplace</h3>
            <p><b>Disparities in Pay:</b>The gender pay gap persists, with men, on average, earning more than women. Factors include occupational segregation, negotiation patterns, and biases in promotion.
                Representation in Leadership: Men are often overrepresented in leadership roles across various industries, contributing to a lack of diversity and potential for perpetuating gender inequalities.
                Occupational Stereotypes: Societal expectations and stereotypes may guide men into certain professions and discourage them from pursuing careers perceived as non-traditional for their gender.</p>
            <a href="#" class="btn">learn more<span class="fas fa-chevron-right"></span></a>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <h3>Fatherhood and Parental Leave:</h3>
            <p><b>Expectations:</b> Expectations surrounding masculinity may influence societal views on men taking parental leave or actively participating in caregiving. These expectations can impact work-life balance for fathers.
            </p>
            <a href="#" class="btn">learn more<span class="fas fa-chevron-right"></span></a>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <h3>Legal and Criminal Justice</h3>
            <p><b> Incarceration Rates:</b> Men face higher rates of incarceration, often influenced by factors like systemic biases, sentencing policies, and socioeconomic conditions.</p>
            <a href="#" class="btn">learn more<span class="fas fa-chevron-right"></span></a>
        </div>
        <div class="box">
            <h3>Mental Health</h3>
            <p><b>Stigma and Help-Seeking Behavior:</b> Societal expectations around masculinity may discourage men from openly discussing mental health issues or seeking professional help. This can lead to underreporting and untreated mental health conditions.</p>  
            <a href="#" class="btn">learn more<span class="fas fa-chevron-right"></span></a>
        </div>

    </div>
